{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"92e2211d-7656-42d5-abcf-5fb8e56a9b84","content":"In .NET MAUI, those methods moved from `Application` to the `Window` class. You have two options:\n\n**1. Override methods on a custom `Window`:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* was OnStart */  }\n    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* was OnSleep */  }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* was OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in `App.xaml.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n```\n\n**2. Subscribe to events inline in `App`:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new MainPage());\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` / `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` / `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `Resumed` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f726dc4-8cd9-4d7b-af52-727eac80bc4a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. Specifically:\n\n- The `Application` class still exists, but the lifecycle is now handled through `Window` events or platform-specific lifecycle events.\n\n\n- You can override `CreateWindow()` in your `Application` class to access window lifecycle events like `Created`, `Resumed`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, and `Destroying`.\n- Alternatively, you can use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` to hook into the application lifecycle at a more granular level.\n\nThe mapping from the old lifecycle methods to the new window-based events is straightforward: `OnStart()` maps to `Window.Created`, `OnResume()` to `Window.Resumed`, and `OnSleep()` to `Window.Stopped`. You can subscribe to these events directly or override the corresponding methods on the `Window` class itself.","outputTokens":831,"requestId":"1015:189FE3:150DA0C:17AA4C6:69FD34A1"},"id":"1b1f9320-685d-43c6-8892-ccd4d888067c","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:56:17.807Z","parentId":"d52866ba-2235-417a-b712-2f4c47242b0a"}
